{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778184249,"nonce":"DKwLM3nH9pYABa0F3T7uHlZMEkI=","title":"Round-trip ratio: bump PI max_iter, tighten test bounds, document the (γ*, γ_design] band","message":"Probe at `scripts/probe_round_trip_ratio.py` (untracked, in worktree `feature/round-trip-horizon-probe`) showed:\n\n```\nHorizon sweep (Q_f=1.0, tol=1e-4)\nn=50  → ratio 0.638 (gamma* shifts at long horizons)\nn=100 → ratio 0.800\nn=200 → ratio 1.201   conv: NO\nn=400 → ratio 1.209   conv: yes\nn=800 → ratio 1.211   conv: NO\n\nQ_f scale sweep (n=200): only matters when amplified ≥10× (then ratio drops below 1.0)\nTol sweep: bisection tolerance is essentially irrelevant (Δ +0.005 across 1e-2..1e-5)\n```\n\n**Reinterpretation:** the original \"ratio should be ≈ 1.0\" framing was wrong. Theory says: a controller designed at `γ_design = 1.5·γ*` has actual closed-loop gain in `(γ*, γ_design]` because γ* is the *infimum*. So ratio ∈ (1.0, 1.5] is correct. The 1.21 plateau at long horizons matches.\n\nThe short-horizon under-count (0.64–0.80) was an artifact of `find_gamma_star` finding a different boundary at short horizons (γ* itself jumps from 0.00943 at n=100 to 0.01375 at n=200) — short-horizon γ* underestimates the long-horizon γ\\*, producing apparent ratio \u003c 1.0.\n\n**Fix:**\n1. Tighten the test bounds in `tests/test_induced_gain.py` round-trip test from `[0.3·γ*, γ_design]` to `(γ*, γ_design]` (allowing equality at γ_design but strict above γ*). Document the rationale.\n2. Bump the default `max_iter` in `induced_gain_power_iteration` to handle long horizons (n ≥ 200) without flagging `conv: NO`. Default 200 → 500 or so.\n3. Update the docstring on `induced_gain_power_iteration` and `induced_gain` to describe the expected band `(γ*, γ_design]` and the regime-dependence of the relationship.\n4. Commit `scripts/probe_round_trip_ratio.py` for future debugging — it's a useful regression-detection tool.\n\nPhase: methodology-fix follow-up. Surfaced from `74bfd86` analyser landing.","files":null}]}